WHAT THIS TILE IS:
This is the AFTERMATH chapter — 1694 through 1711. It must:
- Cover the public reckonings, dated and named: Samuel Sewall's 1697 apology
  in Old South Church (the only judge to recant publicly); the twelve trial
  jurors' 1697 confession of error; the 1702 General Court declaration of
  illegality; Ann Putnam Jr's 1706 apology in Salem Village Church; the 1711
  legislative reversal of attainders and £600 restitution.
- Be honest about what the period did NOT do: full restitution did not arrive
  until centuries later, and several names remained unrestored into the
  twentieth and twenty-first centuries.
- Convey the contrast: the people who ran the trials had, within a generation,
  almost universally distanced themselves from them. And yet the village and
  region carried the weight forward.

